data.name: ToolTipGrowerToFinishProductionSystem
data.value: Grower-to-finish operations house feeder hogs until they are marketed at ~110-115 kg live weight. These operations do not keep breeding animals but purchase their pigs from weaner operations.

data.name: ToolTipFarrowToWeanProductionSystem
data.value: Farrow-to-wean operations house sows, gilts and possibly boars; these operations maintain the breeding stock but sell piglets to iso-wean or grower-to-finish operations.

data.name: ToolTipIsoWeanProductionSystem
data.value: Iso-wean (isolated wean) operations are also called ‘nursery barns’, and house piglets that have been weaned at ~18-28 days old. These animals are kept in isolation from sows and larger hogs to prevent disease transmission. Hogs typically spend 5-8 weeks in a nursery barn, although it can be as little as 2 weeks.

data.name: TooltipRotationComponent
data.value: A component to create a crop rotation. A single crop rotation component can be used instead of multiple field components.

data.name: ToolTipFarrowToFinishProductionSystem
data.value: Farrow-to-finish operations keep and mate sows, farrow litters and raise piglets to market weight.

data.name: ToolTipPulletFarm
data.value: Juvenile females (pullets) are transported from hatcheries to pullet farms or to pullet barns on egg production operations where they remain until they reach breeding age (approximately 18-20 weeks), after which they are moved to egg laying operations/barns.

data.name: ToolTipChickenMultiplierBreeder
data.value: Represents the reproduction portion of bird production where birds that produce eggs for reproduction are managed; these eggs are then sent to reproduction hatcheries to be hatched. In the multiplier breeder operation, adult males and females are housed together.

data.name: ToolTipChickenEggProduction
data.value: Once pullets reach approximately 18-20 weeks of age they are transferred from either separate pullet operations or pullet barns on an egg production operation to egg-laying barns. These hens will produce eggs for up to 71 weeks of age.

data.name: ToolTipTurkeyMultiplierBreeder
data.value: Represents the reproduction portion of bird production where birds that produce eggs for reproduction are managed; these eggs are then sent to reproduction hatcheries to be hatched. In the multiplier breeder operation, male and female turkeys are housed separately for the entire life cycle.

data.name: ToolTipChickenMultiplierHatchery
data.value: Hatcheries receive fertile eggs from multiplier breeder farms, hatch them and then deliver the hatchlings (day old chicks or poults) to pullet farms (female chicks only), to pullet barns on egg-laying operations, or to meat production operations (male and female chicks, for chicken and/or turkey).

data.name: ToolTipTurkeyMeatProduction
data.value: Poults arriving in the operation from a multiplier hatchery are raised to market weight after approximately 12 weeks (turkey broilers) or 16-22 weeks (heavy turkeys)

data.name: ToolTipChickenMeatProduction
data.value: Chicks arriving in the operation from a multiplier hatchery are raised to market weight (1-4 kg, depending on bird type and end product) after approximately 30-56 days (depending on the bird type and rearing system).
